\begin_layout Subsection
The equation of motion
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
pendulum
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hopefully having justified an interest in the pendulum, let us turn to a
 modern derivation of the motion of a pendulum by appealing to the free
 body diagram
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
free body diagram
\end_layout

\end_inset

, a mechanical engineering mainstay.
 In a free body diagram, a body, in this case the bob of a pendulum, is
 isolated from everything except the forces acting on it.
 Those forces are indicated by vectors, and Newton's second law of motion
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Newton ! second law of motion
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (the acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the magnitude
 of the net force applied to the object, in the same direction as the net
 force, and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, or 
\begin_inset Formula $F=ma$
\end_inset

) is applied.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Free-body-diagram"

\end_inset

Free body diagram for a pendulum.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ode-pendulum01.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Free-body-diagram"

\end_inset

 shows the three forces acting on a pendulum---the force of gravity
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
force ! gravitational
\end_layout

\end_inset

; the tension
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
force ! tension
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the rod or string holding the bob to the pivot; and a third force called
 drag
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
force ! drag
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is due to air resistance---along with the directions normal (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{N}$
\end_inset

) and tangential (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{T}$
\end_inset

) to the path of the pendulum.
 Technically only the bob and the three forces are part of the free body
 diagram.
 Nothing else is part of the free body diagram, but is added in dashed lines
 to help describe the motion.
 The length of the pendulum is taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

, and we will apply Newton's second law in the direction tangent to the
 motion.
 That is, in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The speed of the bob is the product of the length of the pendulum and the
 angular speed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 The acceleration of the bob, the derivative of speed, is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}\left(\ell\dot{\theta}\right)=\ell\ddot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Formula $ma$
\end_inset

 (mass times acceleration) term of Newton's second law for the motion of
 a pendulum
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
pendulum
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $ml\ddot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gravity
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
force ! gravitational
\end_layout

\end_inset

 causes a constant downward force on the bob with magnitude equal to the
 weight of the bob, 
\begin_inset Formula $mg$
\end_inset

.
 The magnitude of this force in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{T}$
\end_inset

 direction, however, is 
\begin_inset Formula $mg\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It is worth taking a moment to make sure we have the correct sign.
 For values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 between 0 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, the bob is to the right of the pivot, so the force of gravity tends to
 accelerate the bob in the clockwise (negative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

) direction.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $mg\sin\theta$
\end_inset

 is positive for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 between 0 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, the force due to gravity is actually 
\begin_inset Formula $-mg\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi$
\end_inset

 and 0, the bob is to the left of the pivot, so the force of gravity tends
 to accelerate the bob in the counterclockwise (positive with respect to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

) direction.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $mg\sin\theta$
\end_inset

 is negative for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi$
\end_inset

 and 0, the force due to gravity is again 
\begin_inset Formula $-mg\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Similar analysis for any other angle will lead to the same conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The damping or drag force (air resistance)
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
force ! drag
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is taken as a force proportional to the speed of the bob, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

, so has magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $c\ell\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Damping forces are always taken to directly oppose the motion, so the magnitude
 of damping in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{T}$
\end_inset

, is its entirety.
 It only remains to choose the right sign.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 indicates the direction of motion, the damping force must have the opposite
 sign.
 The damping constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is taken to be positive, and of course 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is positive, so the damping force must be 
\begin_inset Formula $-c\ell\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tension
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
force ! tension
\end_layout

\end_inset

 acting on the bob is irrelevant because it is always perpendicular to the
 motion.
 The component of tension in the tangential direction is always zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the sum of these the tangential forces for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, Newton's second law applied to the pendulum becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $-mg\sin\theta-c\ell\dot{\theta}-0=m\ell\ddot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\theta}+\frac{c}{m}\dot{\theta}+\frac{g}{\ell}\sin\theta=0.\label{eq:pendulum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pendulum"

\end_inset

 is known as a differential equation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
differential equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 because it is an equation that involves derivatives (or differentials).
 To be more precise, it is a second degree ordinary differential equation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
differential equation ! ordinary
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (o.d.e.)
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

o.d.e.|see{differential equation, ordinary}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Second degree
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
differential equation ! degree
\end_layout

\end_inset

 because the highest degree derivative is the second and ordinary because
 it involves only one independent variable (time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
pendulum
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest differential equations are considered in calculus, though the
 term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

differential equation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is rarely used.
 When first discussing the idea of antidifferentiation, the question of
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What function has a derivative equal to ...
 ?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inevitably comes up.
 For example, one might be faced with the question of what function's derivative
 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

? This question can also be asked, what function 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 satisfies the (differential) equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y'=x$
\end_inset

? The answer can be arrived at by integrating the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int y'\, dx & = & \int x\, dx\\
y & = & \frac{1}{2}x^{2}+C
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 (don't forget the constant of integration!)
\end_layout

