\begin_layout Standard
The solution of a differential equation is, in one way, very much like the
 solution of an algebraic equation but, in another way, entirely different.
 For an algebraic equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, for example, we say that we have a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x=s$
\end_inset

 if substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the equation makes the equation true.
 Likewise, for a differential equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, for example, we say that we have a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=s$
\end_inset

 if substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 in the equation makes the equation true.
 The difference is 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a 
\shape italic
number
\shape default
 in the case of an algebraic equation while 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a 
\shape italic
function
\shape default
 in the case of a differential equation.
 We would say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the algebraic equation 
\begin_inset Formula $3x^{2}-8x+4=0$
\end_inset

 since, substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3(2)^{2}-8(2)+4=0,
\]

\end_inset

a true statement.
 Analogously, we would say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=e^{2t}$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the differential equation 
\begin_inset Formula $3\ddot{\theta}-8\dot{\theta}+4\theta=0$
\end_inset

 since, substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2t}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3(4e^{2t})-8(2e^{2t})+4(e^{2t})=0,
\]

\end_inset

again a true statement.
 Notice that the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 need to be calculated in order to complete the substitution.
\end_layout

