\begin_layout Standard
As with algebraic equations, differential equations may have more than one
 solution.
 We already saw that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=e^{2t}$
\end_inset

 is a solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $3\ddot{\theta}-8\dot{\theta}+4\theta=0$
\end_inset

.
 So are 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=5e^{2t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=-2.1e^{2t}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\sqrt{7\pi}e^{2t}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=ce^{2t}$
\end_inset

 is a solution for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 The ode 
\begin_inset Formula $3\ddot{\theta}-8\dot{\theta}+4\theta=0$
\end_inset

 has infinitely many solutions! It is a straightforward exercise to check.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=ce^{2t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}=2ce^{2t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\theta}=4ce^{2t}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
3\ddot{\theta}-8\dot{\theta}+4\theta & = & 3(4ce^{2t})-8(2ce^{2t})+4(ce^{2t})\\
 & = & 12c(e^{2t})-16c(e^{2t})+4c(e^{2t})\\
 & = & (12c-16c+4c)e^{2t}\\
 & = & 0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Even more, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=ae^{2t/3}$
\end_inset

 is a solution for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 This solution can be verified just as the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=ce^{2t}$
\end_inset

 was verified.
 Can you do it? Answer 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "odeMoreSolutions"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=ce^{2t}+ae^{2t/3}$
\end_inset

 is also a solution for any pair of constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

! Can you show it? Answer 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "odeEvenMoreSolutions"

\end_inset

.
 It is not uncommon for a differential equation to have infinitely many
 solutions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another differential equation with infinitely many solutions is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{y}=\frac{t}{y}.
\]

\end_inset

The solutions are 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-\sqrt{t^{2}+a}$
\end_inset

, valid for any constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Complex solutions are valid! However, if we also require 
\begin_inset Formula $y(0)=1$
\end_inset

, there is only one solution! 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-\sqrt{t^{2}+c}$
\end_inset

 is no longer a solution because it gives negative values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+c}$
\end_inset

 is only a solution if 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\shape italic
one and only
\shape default
 solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $y(0)=1$
\end_inset

 is called an initial value, or initial condition, and the pair of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{y} & = & \frac{t}{y}\\
y(0) & = & 1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 is called an initial value problem.
 More generally, the pair of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{y} & = & f(y,t)\\
y(t_{0}) & = & y_{0}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

forms what is knows as a first order initial value problem.
