\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{\sqrt{t^{2}+1}}(2t)=\frac{t}{\sqrt{t^{2}+1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=\frac{t}{y}$
\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{t}{\sqrt{t^{2}+1}}=\frac{t}{\sqrt{t^{2}+1}},
\]

\end_inset

an undeniably true statement.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

 is a solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=\frac{t}{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $y(0)=\sqrt{0^{2}+1}=1$
\end_inset

, so the particular solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $y(0)=1$
\end_inset

 also.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\shape italic
one
\shape default
 solution---and the only solution of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+c}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-\sqrt{t^{2}+a}$
\end_inset

.
 But is it 
\shape italic
the only
\shape default
 solution of any form? Perhaps there are other functions that satisfy the
 differential equation.
 A little bit of calculus should help settle the issue.
 The demonstration hinges on showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-\sqrt{t^{2}+a}$
\end_inset

 are 
\shape italic
the only
\shape default
 solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=\frac{t}{y}$
\end_inset

.
 The following sequence of equations show it.
 Each line implies the next.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{dy}{dt} & = & \frac{t}{y},\qquad y\neq0\\
y\, dy & = & t\, dt,\qquad y\neq0\\
\int y\, dy & = & C+\int t\: dt,\qquad y\neq0\\
\frac{1}{2}y^{2} & = & C+\frac{1}{2}t^{2},\qquad y\neq0\\
y^{2} & = & 2C+t^{2},\qquad y\neq0\\
y & = & \pm\sqrt{t^{2}+2C},\qquad y\neq0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Replacing the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $2C$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 does not change the fact that the term is an arbitrary constant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{t^{2}+c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-\sqrt{t^{2}+a}$
\end_inset

 are the only solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=\frac{t}{y}$
\end_inset

.
 This method of solving the differential equation is called separation of
 variables
